arch:property.oc:show_val: A medium-sized unit, although it came from a large deposit (approximately 250 liters in the ground). Very much dominated by sheep-sized bone but with several pieces of cattle-sized animals as well. Heavily processed: few fragments more 3-4 cm long. Few diagnostics, therefore, and those largely teeth, carpals/tarsals, and phalanges. Only caprines and cattle are represented among the diagnostics. All caprine body parts appear present; are lots of long bone shaft splinters, some ribs and vertebrae, some pelvis fragments. A range of ages also represented among the caprines. Surface condition generally good (light-moderate weathering). Around 10% of unit burned, mostly to the point of thorough charring; much carbonization and some calcination. Looks like long time at low temperature. Some digestion. Not much coherence, although coherence would likely be masked by the degree of fragmentation. 3 long bones with cut marks. 2 bone points--1 complete, 1 fragment. Looks like fill. Not a street because not trampled. Last number dry sieve= F280. Flot Sample S16 F numbers 281-304 Primarily sheep-goat and caprine-sized animals represented. Carpals and tarsals, a couple of teeth, some long bone and vertebral fragments, and a few fragments from other body parts. Plenty of digestion, very little burning. Flot sample 6; very similar to rest of unit, unsurprisingly. F numbers 305-321. Did contain a couple of small carnivore specimens--more precise identification was hampered by digestion. NR 2007: Sample 1 >4mm flotation 100% sorted, recorded as diagnostics and flot frags only. Moderate size sample, pretty similar to the rest of the unit: quite fragmented, variable surface condition but not looking trampled. Looks like fill. Sample 12 >4mm flotation 100% sorted, recorded as diagnostics and flot frags only. Very similar to sample 1, with a bit less burning and large mammal. Even more so than sample 1, most of the diagnostics are digested

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
